message.content: The president of the United States in 1996 was Bill Clinton. He was sworn into office on January 20, 1993, and served two terms, leaving office on January 20, 2001. During his presidency, Clinton oversaw a period of economic prosperity known as the "dot-com boom," passed major legislation like the North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA) and the Violent Crime Control and Law Enforcement Act, and dealt with various international crises including the genocide in Rwanda and the conflict in Bosnia.
